One Line Plot - Points and Lines

Walter Xie

09/02/2017

library(gg1L)

Scatter plot

Create random coordinates for 2 clusters:

library(ComMA)
df.clusters <- ComMA::random2Clusters()
df.clusters$labels <- rownames(df.clusters)
df.clusters[1:3,]
##          x        y group labels
## 1 1.673964 2.437651     A      1
## 2 2.552462 1.928776     A      2
## 3 1.325056 4.163509     A      3

Scatter plots may have overlaps between data points and axises. unclip.ggplot can turns off clipping, but it returns a gtable object, so that either pdf.gtplot or plot.gtable will be used to handle the plot.

gg.plot <- ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", shape.id="group", 
                         title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)
# turns off clipping
g.table <- unclip.ggplot(gg.plot) 
plot(g.table)

Some tricks

Add expand_limits after ggplot object to expend x and y axes:

gg.plot + expand_limits(x = c(-1, 6), y=c(-1, 10))

ellipsed.id=“group” creates ellipses by groups, text.id=“labels” defines the column for labels, xintercept=0 and yintercept=0 sets the coordinate axes, and text.data=subset(df.clusters, x > 3 & y > 6) selectively labels the points at x > 3 and y > 6:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", ellipsed.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.data=subset(df.clusters, x > 3 & y > 6), xintercept=0, yintercept=0,  
              title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.or.point controls appearance of labels and points:

  • if 1, then display the texts only;
  • if 2, then only points;
  • if 3, the default, then both the texts and points.

For example, show only labels:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, title="Clusters", palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.repel uses geom_text_repel from ggrepel package to avoid overlapped texts. It is better than text.avoid.overlap, where the latter sometime removes overlapped texts.

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, text.repel=T, title="Clusters (text.repel=T)", 
              palette="Set1", verbose=F)

text.avoid.overlap uses check_overlap in geom_text from ggplot2 package:

ggScatterPlot(df.clusters, x.id="x", y.id="y", colour.id="group", text.id="labels", 
              text.or.point=1, text.avoid.overlap=T, title="Clusters (text.avoid.overlap=T)", 
              palette="Set1", verbose=F)

Non-metric multidimensional scaling

Load the example data reads.phyla, where x is one of genetic marks, and the numbers are eDNA sequences (reads) identified as the phylum listed in y:

data(reads.phyla)
reads.phyla[1:2,]
##                16S 18S trnL ITS COI COI-spun TaxaGroup
## Actinobacteria 958   1  301   4   7        0  Bacteria
## Aquificae        0   0   10   0   0        0  Bacteria

Because the functions to compute NMDS metaMDS, PCoA cmdscale, and PCA prcomp take different input data, please make sure you give a valid input for different NMDS plots.

NMDS using metaMDS

The following Nonmetric Multidimensional Scaling (NMDS) plot illustrates how the phyla are different in term of their reads abundances in 6 markers, and the data frame reads.phyla[,7, drop=F] provides the groups used for colouring texts.

nmds <- gtNMDSPlot(reads.phyla[,1:6], reads.phyla[,7, drop=F], colour.id="TaxaGroup", 
                   text.or.point=2, verbose=F)

PCoA using cmdscale

It is a classical MDS and also known as principal coordinates analysis (Gower, 1966).

require(vegan)
dist.cm <- vegdist(reads.phyla[,1:6], method="jaccard", binary=TRUE)
cmds <- gtClassicalMDSPlot(dist.cm, reads.phyla[,7, drop=F], colour.id="TaxaGroup", 
                   text.or.point=1, text.avoid.overlap=T, verbose=F)
plot(cmds)

PCA using prcomp

prcomp rotates the input to analyse on columns, so that we have the plot of 6 markers whose differences are in term of the abundances of phyla,

pca <- gtPCAPlot(reads.phyla[,1:6], text.or.point=3, text.size=5, text.repel=T, verbose=F)
plot(pca)
